# Navigation Rules (go_router)

Navigation is a **core architectural boundary**, not a UI convenience.

All navigation must be:
- typed
- declarative
- deep-link safe
- feature-owned
- testable
- free of business logic inside widgets

---

# 1. Core Requirements

## MUST

- [ ] use `go_router` as the only navigation system
- [ ] use `go_router_builder` for typed routes
- [ ] support deep linking for ALL public routes
- [ ] enforce protected-route access via router-level `redirect` when session/auth exists (not widget checks)
- [ ] define typed routes in `apps/eddyscout/lib/routing/` (today) or feature modules as they gain routes
- [ ] keep a single global route graph (today: `goRouterProvider` in `app_router_provider.dart`; target: compose in `packages/routing/`)

---

## MUST NOT

- ❌ use `Navigator.push/pop`
- ❌ use `MaterialPageRoute`
- ❌ embed navigation logic inside widgets
- ❌ bypass router for “quick navigation fixes”

---

# 2. Routing Architecture Rules

## Feature-Owned Routes

Each feature MUST:

- declare its own route subtree
- define route parameters via typed route classes
- expose routes via public API only

---

## Central Router Composition

- **today:** app owns `GoRouter` in `apps/eddyscout/lib/routing/`; `packages/routing/` is a scaffold (see `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`)
- **target:** compose feature route subtrees in `packages/routing/`
- only one global route graph; features MUST NOT depend on each other’s route definitions directly

---

# 3. Typed Routing (MANDATORY)

## Required Tooling

- `go_router_builder`

---

## Rules

- [ ] all routes must be typed (`@TypedGoRoute`)
- [ ] path + query params must be strongly typed fields
- [ ] no string-based route definitions for public navigation

---

## MUST NOT

- use raw string routes in app code
- manually construct URLs in widgets
- bypass generated route helpers

---

# 4. Navigation Methods

## context.go()

- [ ] use for **replacement navigation**
- [ ] resets navigation stack
- [ ] used for top-level transitions (login → home, tab switching)

---

## context.push()

- [ ] use only when back-stack is required
- [ ] used for drill-down navigation (detail pages, modals)

---

## Rule

> If user expects "back" behavior → use `push()`
> If user does NOT expect back behavior → use `go()`

---

# 5. Stateful Navigation (Tabs / Shells)

> Required **when** adding tab-based or multi-stack navigation. Not used in the current single-stack app.

## Required Pattern

- use `StatefulShellRoute` for tab-based layouts
- maintain independent navigation stacks per tab
- preserve state across tab switching

---

## Rules

- [ ] each tab has isolated navigator stack
- [ ] switching tabs must not reset inner navigation
- [ ] deep links must resolve to correct shell branch

---

# 6. Deep Linking Rules (CRITICAL)

## Required

- [ ] all public routes must be deep-linkable
- [ ] app must restore correct navigation state from cold start
- [ ] invalid deep links must fallback safely

---

## Validation

- [ ] test cold start navigation
- [ ] test direct URL entry
- [ ] test malformed URL handling

---

# 7. Parameter Passing Rules

## Allowed

- path parameters
- query parameters

---

## FORBIDDEN

- ❌ `extra:` for passing business-critical data
- ❌ passing complex objects through navigation layer
- ❌ relying on runtime object reconstruction in routes

---

## Rule

> Navigation must remain serializable and deep-link safe at all times.

---

# 8. Auth & Guard Rules

> Required **when** adding login, session, or role-protected routes. Today the app uses platform/token redirects in `app_router_provider.dart`, not session auth guards.

## Required

- auth checks MUST happen in router `redirect`
- use Riverpod or equivalent auth state provider
- redirect unauthenticated users to login route

---

## MUST NOT

- check authentication inside widgets
- manually block UI rendering for protected routes
- duplicate auth logic across screens

---

# 9. Error & Edge Case Handling

- [ ] invalid routes must redirect to safe fallback screen
- [ ] missing parameters must not crash app
- [ ] expired sessions must redirect cleanly
- [ ] deep links must fail gracefully

---

# 10. Testing Requirements

## Must test:

- deep link resolution
- navigation stack behavior
- auth redirects
- tab state preservation
- invalid route fallback

---

# 11. Performance Rules

- [ ] avoid rebuilding entire router unnecessarily
- [ ] keep route definitions modular
- [ ] avoid heavy logic in route builders
- [ ] lazy-load feature routes where possible

---

# 12. Anti-Patterns (DO NOT DO)

## MUST NOT

- use Navigator API directly
- bypass typed routing system
- pass objects via `extra`
- put navigation logic inside widgets
- duplicate route definitions across features
- hardcode route strings

---

